Reported by https://support.atlassian.com/browse/JSP-55498

I am developing a listener to send XML email to a specific email address. My listener is able to send the email when I add a NotificationRecipient like this (taken from the MailListener source code, available on this page: [http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Listeners]):
{code}
NotificationRecipient notificationRecipient = (NotificationRecipient) iterator1.next();
{code}

If I replace the above line with this one:
{code}
NotificationRecipient notificationRecipient = new NotificationRecipient("myemail@mycompany.com");
{code}

The email gets added to the queue (I can see it in the JIRA administrative interface), but I don't receive it. By the way, I have double-checked my email address...

I have checked the following methods, and the produce the same result with both of the examples above:
{code}
notificationRecipient.getEmail()
notificationRecipient.getFormat()
notificationRecipient.isHtml()
{code}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-20812].
  {panel}

I'd like to be able to sort issues by their fix version's release date. Typical use-case: developers should be fixing issues assigned to them in the order of decreasing priority, sorted by the release date. At our company, developers using the "issues assign to me" filter often make the mistake of working on high priority issues that are assigned to a version very far into the future.

There is no (obvious) way to achieve this.

If you enter in URL that points to an action that does not exist (e.g. secure/project/ViewProect.jspa) you get a strange page with:

{quote}
"HTTP Status 404 - Could not execute action [ViewProect]:Action 'ViewProect' not found or could not be initialized a class with that name could"
{quote}

I think you should get a 500 page instead of this random and badly formatted error message. A 500 page is displayed if you put in a bad command name (e.g. jira/secure/project/ViewProject!dhdhdh.jspa).

